<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn1>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn1' href="#_ednref1"
name="_edn1" title=""></a><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'>Notes<o:p></o:p></span></i></p>

<p class=MsoEndnoteText><span lang=EN-US><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoEndnoteText><span lang=EN-US><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=NormaaliChar1 style='text-indent:0mm'><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[1]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> In the I-mode case there
may<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>be a group reason<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>involved but it is had privately. A we-mode
group reason, say R, can only be had when functioning as a group member. In contrast,
R can be a person’s I-mode reason when he is functioning merely as a private
person. Functioning in the we-mode is necessarily connected to a group reason
while functioning in the I-mode is only contingently connected to the group
reason (when there happens to be one involved). When R is a we-mode group
reason There are the following three possibilities for intending in the I-mode:
1) the person functions solely as a private person, 2) the person is a member
of an I-mode group, viz a collective in a broad sense in which the participants
are only privately committed to the group (see Chapter 1 of Tuomela, 2005b, for
I-mode and we-mode groups), or 3) the person is a member of a we-mode group but
only functions as a group member in a weak, I-mode sense of acting as rather
than in the we-mode sense. (Cf. the comments related to non-operative members
in Section IV as illustrating this possibility.)<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn2>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn2' href="#_ednref2"
name="_edn2" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[2]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> Cf. Tuomela (1984),
(1995), (2000) and Tuomela and Miller (1988).<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn3>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn3' href="#_ednref3"
name="_edn3" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[3]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Jointly seeing to it that something is the
case can be used as umbrella notion to cover many kinds of activities – e.g.
jointly performing actions in a direct or in an indirect sense, jointly
bringing about states, jointly maintaining states, and so on (cf. Sandu and
Tuomela, 1996, and Belnap et al., 2001). Notice however, that in the context of
joint intention the actions in question can be of various kinds, as just
mentioned, and they can be non-equivalent (e.g. joint seeing to it that
something is the case does not entail direct performance, nor is the converse
true). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn4>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn4' href="#_ednref4"
name="_edn4" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[4]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> In other words, there is
the activity in which the participants see to it that the (second part of the)
content comes about and there is the very activity that makes the content
obtain. Thus the participants might hire some other agents to build a house.
Here the first kind of activity is hiring the agents and monitoring their work;
and building the house (performed by the hired agents) is the second kind of
activity. In this paper I will, as said, mainly speak of the case of the
(direct) performance and acting together. (See Tuomela, 2000, Chapter 2, for
discussion.)<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn5>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn5' href="#_ednref5"
name="_edn5" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[5]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-GB style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB'> A
linguistic formulation that typically seems apt for aim-intentions is
”intending that something be the case”, however, taken with the understanding
that an aim-intending agent is still required actively to contribute to the
coming about of the state in question (and this conceptual condition is in
general independent of whether realizing it is rational for him or not).<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn6>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn6' href="#_ednref6"
name="_edn6" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[6]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> See Bratman (1999), p.
125ff.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>and Miller (1995), p. 64, Gilbert
(1990), pp. 6-9.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn7>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn7' href="#_ednref7"
name="_edn7" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[7]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> The collective acceptance
of an intention as the group’s intention entails the satisfaction of the
so-called Collectivity Condition. Applied to satisfaction, the Collectivity
Condition says, roughly, that necessarily, if the joint intention (goal) is
(semantically) satisfied for one of the participants, then it is satisfied for
all participants. (Note that here we are speaking of the participants personal
intentions in the we-mode, not in the I-mode.) <o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn8>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn8' href="#_ednref8"
name="_edn8" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[8]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> Here is a comment on
Velleman’s (1997) account. He considers joint intention (or “shared intention”,
in his terminology) in the two-person case as follows.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Suppose that joint intention between two
persons is formed by the following exchange. The first person says “I will if
you will”, where “I will” is taken to express an intention to participate in a
joint action. The other person might say “Well, I will if you will” (cf.
Velleman, 1997, p. 38). What we have here is a regress of the kind “I will if
you will, but you will if I will, but …”, as long as no further assumptions are
made (see e.g. Tuomela, 2005, for the regress problem). But according to
Velleman, “[y]our responding with ‘Well, I will if you will’ perversely calls
into question whether I have in fact willed” (p. 45). According to him, the
proper response to “I will if you will” is “Then I will”. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>The above response “Well, I will if you will” may in a coordination
situation express a conditional intention to participate in a joint action or
it may express only a (causal) condition for one’s forming the intention to
participate. As the latter interpretation poses no particular philosophical
problem, I assume Velleman takes the above saying to refer to properly
conditional intentions (see Velleman, 1997, p. 46). Then it is not right to say
that the response “Well, I will if you will” perversely questions my willing,
because it does acknowledge that I intend – albeit that I intend only
conditionally, the condition being your intention. The verbal response “Then I
will” does not perform the task of deconditionalization except under further
assumptions left implicit in the pragmatics of the situation. Thus Velleman’s
solution does not theoretically work as such in our hard problem cases
(although it of course does normally work in the context of our shared social
practice of verbally making agreements). The approach is basically wrong
because it does not start from a we-perspective (like the Bulletin Board View
of Tuomela, 2005b), where we-ness and the idea that a joint project is under
way is already presupposed (be the presupposition right or wrong). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn9>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn9' href="#_ednref9"
name="_edn9" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[9]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Cf. the third clause in my analysis (<i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>WI</i>) of we-intentions below in Section
III.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn10>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn10' href="#_ednref10"
name="_edn10" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[10]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> This activity in general
requires public exchange of information between them if it is to lead to
mutually known (and not only mutually believed) unconditional participation
intentions. Another reason for publicity in a group context is that such
central social notions as the speech acts of agreement making, promising,
commanding, and informing – all relevant to joint-intention formation – are in
their core sense not only language-dependent but public.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn11>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn11' href="#_ednref11"
