<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn15>

<p class=Normaali-jatko align=left style='text-align:left'><a style='mso-endnote-id:
edn15' href="#_ednref15" name="_edn15" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
12.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman";
mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;
mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[15]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;line-height:150%'>
From the point of view of the logical form of joint intentions, we-intentions,
and group intentions the following rather trivial point is central to keep in
mind. A joint intention can<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>be<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>expressed by an (m+1)-place predicate JI(A<sub>1</sub>,...,A<sub>m</sub>,X)
standing<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>for “the<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>agents<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
</span>A<sub>1</sub>,...,A<sub>m</sub> jointly, as a group, intend to
perform<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>the<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>action<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
</span>X jointly”. Here “as a group” can be symbolized by assuming that the
agents function as proper group members thus as members of a “we”, and we have
WE(A<sub>1</sub>,...,A<sub>m</sub>,X). The agents thus form a thick “we” at
least concerning X. This “togetherness-we” can be cashed out by saying that the
agents have collectively accepted joint action X as the agents’ “goal” or as
what they are to perform together for the group they form, being collectively
committed to performing X jointly. In this context, each member A<sub>i </sub><span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'> </span>has the we-intention to perform X (viz. each A<sub>i
</sub><span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> </span>intends to<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>perform X together with the others as
expressed by “We will do X”). This is symbolized by WI(A<sub>i</sub> , X). The
account (<i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>WI</i>) in the text gives an
analysis of what this involves. Finally, we can speak of a group’s intention to
perform an action, such as X, here. This is symbolized by I(g,X). In our simple
case g consists precisely of A<sub>1</sub>,...,A<sub>m</sub>.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>In this case JI(A<sub>1</sub>,...,A<sub>m</sub>,X)
and I(g,X) are truth equivalent, the two sides of one and the same coin, so to
speak. In more interesting cases, where the group involves the distinction
between authorized operative and non-operative members, the account (<i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>GINT</i>) to be stated below, gives the
connection.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoEndnoteText style='line-height:150%'><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[15]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span><span
lang=EN-US><span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Recall that I have
characterized the we-mode in terms of three features: (1) the attitude or
action must be collectively accepted as the group’s attitude or action, (2) it
must be for the use and, typically, benefit of the group, and (3) the
participants must be collectively committed to the attitude or action.</span><span
style='mso-ansi-language:FI'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

