<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn21>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn21' href="#_ednref21"
name="_edn21" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[21]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> This is what Searle,
1990, p. 405, says: “We are tempted to construe ‘doing his part’ to mean doing
his part toward achieving the collective goal. But if we adopt that move, then
we have included the notion of a collective intention in the notion of ‘doing
his part.’ We are thus faced with a dilemma: if we include the notion of
collective intention in the notion of ‘doing his part,’ the analysis fails
because of circularity; we would now be defining we-intentions in terms of
we-intentions. If we don’t so construe ‘doing his part’, then the analysis
fails because of inadequacy.” (Cf. also S. Miller, 2001, pp. 71-73.)<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>In Tuomela (2005a) I respond to this charge
and claim that while there is some circularity, it is not vicious. On the
whole, Searle’s discussion of the Tuomela-Miller (1988) paper is based on a
massive misunderstanding probably based on his not having properly read the
paper, as I have shown elsewhere (e.g. in Tuomela, 1995).<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

