lang=EN-US> See Bratman (1999), p. 114, Schmitt (2003) and Tuomela (2005b),
Chapter 3, for the fact that joint action is not required in Bratman’s account.</span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn31>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn31' href="#_ednref31"
name="_edn31" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[31]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> Cf. Gilbert (1989) and
her later works. Gilbert is not specific about the jointly intending
participants’ attitudes. What happens in their personal minds when they
participate in a joint intention? As seen, my elaborate answer goes in terms of
we-intention and intention to perform one’s part.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn32>

<p class=MsoEndnoteText style='line-height:150%'><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn32'
href="#_ednref32" name="_edn32" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US><span style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-ansi-language:
EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[32]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US> Searle claims that collective intentions are irreducible to
individual intentions and mutual beliefs. However, when he actually tries to
spell this out, he does not succeed in showing that collective intentions are
different kinds of intentions, and indeed ends up with individual ”by-means-of
” intentions. This is argued by Zaibert (2003). Futhermore, as argued by
Meijers (2003), Searle’s account is atomistic and does not account for
interpersonal relations and in particular not for the social commitments that
the participants are taken to have in relation to each other.</span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn33>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn33' href="#_ednref33"
name="_edn33" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[33]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> The I-mode/ we-mode
distinction is different from the selfishness/altruism distinction. In the
present example I might as well have aimed to benefit you but contingently
ended up benefiting (also) myself.</span><span lang=EN-GB style='font-size:
10.0pt;line-height:150%;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn34>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn34' href="#_ednref34"
name="_edn34" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[34]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> One can also list other
features of the we-mode which are different from the features of the I-mode.
One feature still worth emphasizing is<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
</span>that the notion of a part of a joint action X is not conceptually
reducible to individual actions, as e.g. Seumas Miller’s theory assumes. One’s
part depends crucially on X and may not be antecedently fixable. Think of. the
practical inference schema (W2) which may generate new elements into one’s part
during the course of the performance of the joint action. This shows that there
are in principle indefinitely many factors that may enter the situation during
action. The part cannot be fully specified beforehand. However, the present
point seems not to apply to Bratman’s theory, as he only speaks about “our
J-ing” in his account.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn35>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn35' href="#_ednref35"
name="_edn35" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[35]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> Cf. </span><span
lang=EN-GB style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB'>Bratman
(1999).<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn36>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><a style='mso-endnote-id:edn36' href="#_ednref36"
name="_edn36" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-font-kerning:12.0pt;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:
EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'>[36]</span></span><![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%'> A shared we-attitude
analysis of I-mode joint intention also yields something very similar. Here is
the account of I-mode joint action that I have recently proposed in Tuomela
(2005b):<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>You and I intentionally performed X together if and only if<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>(1) X is a collective action type, viz., an “achievement-whole” divisible
– either ex ante actu or ex post actu -- into A’s and B’s parts;<sup><o:p></o:p></sup></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>(2) We shared the (reason-based, see below) I-mode intention to perform X
together;<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>(3) We performed X together in accordance with and partly because of our
shared I-mode intention to perform X (or some “closely related” action) together.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>(4) You and I mutually believed – or at least shared the belief – that
(1), (2), and (3).<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>(5) (2) in part because of (4).<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>In (2) we use the following analysis of I-mode shared we-attitude
analysis of intention: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>You and I share (in the I-mode sense) the intention to jointly perform X
if and only if<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>1) I intend that we X in the reason-based we-attitude sense (viz. I
intend that we X in part because I believe that you intend in the reason-based
sense that we X and that we mutually believe that each of us so intends), and <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>2) you similarly intend that we X in the reason-based we-attitude sense.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=Normaali-jatko><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;line-height:
150%'>(Space does not allow a discussion of the above I-mode account.)<o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

<div style='mso-element:endnote' id=edn37>

